<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06196010 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06196010 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SPACE; RESEARCH; RELATION; CALIFORNIA; STATE; ECONOMY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  NASA claims that its space station project already employs nearly 100,000people, directly or indirectly. California, for example, had $540 millionworth of space-station contracts last year, with 3,585 workers.;    Locally,the project is particularly important to Lockheed Missiles andamp; Space Co. ofSunnyvale, Silicon Valley's largest corporate employer, with a payroll of20,700. Lockheed has about 400 of those employees working on several aspectsof the space station, including software for the station's computers and solarpanels.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PROJECT'S PLACE IN CALIFORNIA'S ECONOMY  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See also related story on page 1A of this section.  </MEMO><TEXT>     More important, Lockheed is counting on getting more than $1 billion incontracts as the station moves toward readiness to launch, helping tocompensate for the company's declining defense business.;    At least threeother local organizations have smaller roles in the space station:;    (check)Loral Corp. in Palo Alto, Sunnyvale and San Jose is developing power and videosystems.;    (check) ILC Technology Inc. of Sunnyvale is designing interiorlighting and camera lights for robots that will help assemble the station.;   (check) NASA/Ames Research Center in Mountain View has about 25 scientistsworking on related research such as supporting astronauts in space forextended periods.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  -- Mercury News staff and wire services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910714  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  12A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  193  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday July 14, 199100196010,SJ1  </DATELINE>